  "prompt": "What is the best gaming PC I can get for 1400\u20ac?",
  "response": "As of my last update in October 2023, you can build a powerful gaming PC for around 1400\u20ac. Here's a breakdown of components that would provide excellent performance for gaming:\n\n### Recommended Build:\n\n1. **CPU**: \n   - **AMD Ryzen 5 7600X** or **Intel Core i5-13600K**\n     - Both offer excellent gaming performance and multitasking capabilities.\n\n2. **CPU Cooler**: \n   - **Cooler Master Hyper 212 Black Edition** (if not using a stock cooler)\n   - Or an **All-in-One (AIO) liquid cooler** like the NZXT Kraken X53 if you prefer better cooling and aesthetics.\n\n3. **Motherboard**: \n   - **For AMD**: MSI B650M Mortar or ASUS TUF Gaming B650-Plus\n   - **For Intel**: ASUS TUF Gaming B660M-Plus or MSI MAG B660M Mortar\n\n4. **RAM**:\n   - **32GB (2x16GB) DDR5 6000MHz** (such as Corsair Vengeance or G.Skill Ripjaws)\n   - 32GB is more than enough for gaming and future-proofing.\n\n5. **GPU**:\n   - **NVIDIA GeForce RTX 4060 Ti** or **AMD Radeon RX 7700 XT**\n   - These cards offer great performance for 1080p and even 1440p gaming.\n\n6. **Storage**:\n   - **SSD**: 1TB NVMe SSD (like Samsung 970 EVO Plus or Crucial P5 Plus)\n   - Optional: 2TB HDD for additional storage (Seagate Barracuda or WD Blue)\n\n7. **Power Supply**: \n   - **750W 80+ Gold rated PSU** (such as Corsair RM750x or EVGA SuperNOVA 750 G5)\n\n8. **Case**: \n   - **Mid-Tower ATX case** with good airflow, such as NZXT H510, Fractal Design Meshify C, or Corsair 4000D.\n\n9. **Operating System**:\n   - Windows 10/11 (if you don't have a license already)\n   - You can also consider a Linux distribution if you're open to alternatives, as it's free.\n\n### Example Pricing Breakdown:\n- CPU: ~300\u20ac\n- Cooler: ~50-100\u20ac\n- Motherboard: ~150-250\u20ac\n- RAM: ~100-150\u20ac\n- GPU: ~400-600\u20ac\n- Storage: ~100-150\u20ac\n- PSU: ~100-150\u20ac\n- Case: ~75-150\u20ac\n- OS: ~100\u20ac (if needed)\n\n### Total: ~1400\u20ac\n\n### Tips:\n- **Check prices regularly**: PC component prices fluctuate, so check different retailers for the best deals.\n- **Second-hand components**: Consider buying some components second-hand, such as the GPU, to save money.\n- **Compatibility**: Use a website like PCPartPicker to ensure compatibility between parts.\n\nThis build will ensure you can play most modern games at high settings with excellent frame rates. Always adjust based on your preferences, availability of parts, and potential sales!",
